properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Beeac, Weering.

  • There is a grassfire at Eurack Rd, Beeac that is under control.
  • This Advice message replaces the Advice issued at 12.50pm. 
  • This grassfire is now travelling in a direction towards Weering School Road
There is currently no threat to you, but you should stay informed and monitor conditions.
What you should do: 
  • Keep the roads clear as emergency services are working in the area.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby communities and roads. 
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

The next update is expected by 06/12/2023 06:40 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Thomson River downstream of Wandocka.

MODERATE FLOODING CONTINUES TO EASE VERY SLOWLY AT SALE WHARF

River levels are easing throughout the Thomson River catchment.

No significant rainfall has been observed across the catchment over the last few days.

Further showers and rain areas are forecast from Friday which may cause renewed river level rises. The situation will be monitored closely.

Thomson River downstream of Wandocka:
Moderate flooding is occurring along the Thomson River downstream of Wandocka.

The Thomson River at Sale Wharf is currently at 3.01 metres and falling slowly, just above the moderate flood level (3.00 m). The Thomson River at Sale Wharf is expected to fall below the moderate flood level (3.00 m) by early Wednesday afternoon. The river level is likely to remain above the minor flood level (2.40m) during Wednesday and Thursday.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
What you should do:
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.

Impacts in your area:

  • Parks, hiking tracks and campgrounds may be closed due to flooding. To find out more go to www.parkweb.vic.gov.au/safety/flood-affected-parks.
Road Closures:
  • Additional roads may be damaged from heavy rain including large potholes. Please drive to the conditions. 
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 07/12/2023 11:30 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Community Information is being issued for Burramboot, Colbinabbin, Corop, Lake Cooper, Myola, Runnymede .

  • There is a haystack fire at Burramboot. 
  • Haystack fires are not likely to spread into grassland but do generate a lot of smoke.
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby roads and communities as firefighters pull apart the hay to extinguish the fire. 
  • Firefighters are attending to this fire. 
  • This Community Information message replaces the advise message issued at 10.25am Thursday 6/12/2023.
There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required.
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

Unless the situation changes, this will be the last message issued for this fire.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 

  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.
  • VicEmergency app.
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:

  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to cal VicEmergency
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This is a Final Minor Flood Warning for Snowy River to McKillops Bridge:
 
RIVER LEVELS HAVE FALLEN BELOW MINOR FLOOD LEVELS AT BASIN CREEK, JARRAHMOND AND ORBOST

No significant rainfall totals have been recorded across the Snowy River catchment in the last 48 hours to9:00 am Wednesday.

Flooding has eased across the Snowy River Catchment with river levels expected to remain below the minor flood levels.

Further showers and rain areas are forecast from Friday which may cause renewed river level rises. 

Bombala River:
No further flooding is expected in the Bombala River.  The Bombala River at Bombala is currently at 1.29 metres and falling, below the minor flood level (3.00metres).

Snowy River to McKillops Bridge:

No further flooding is expected in the Snowy River to McKillops Bridge. 
No river level observations are available for the Snowy River at McKillops Bridge, however the river level is expected to be below the minor flood level (2.50 m). The Snowy River at McKillops Bridge is expected to remain below the minor flood level (2.50 m) during Wednesday.

Buchan River:

No further flooding is expected in the Buchan River.
The Buchan River at Buchan is currently at 1.86 metres and falling, below the minor flood level (2.50metres).
The threat of flooding is reduced. Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and beware of hazards remaining in the warning area.
What you should do:

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

If your home or business has been flooded:
  • Check for building damage before you enter.
  • Have all electrical and gas equipment professionally tested before use.
  • Clean and dry out the building as soon as possible.

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Damage to roads and buildings caused by flooding may still exist in your area. 
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides – be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This will be the last warning for this flood. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Latrobe River downstream of Traralgon Creek.

ROSEDALE STEADY AROUND A PROLONGED MINOR FLOOD PEAK

Minor flooding is likely to continue over the next few days along the Latrobe River at Rosedale.

No significant rainfall has been observed across the catchment over the last few days.

Further showers and rain areas are forecast from Friday which may cause renewed river level rises. The situation will be monitored closely.

Latrobe River downstream of Traralgon:
Minor flooding is occurring along the Latrobe River downstream of Traralgon.

The Latrobe River at Rosedale (Main Stream) is currently at 4.33 metres and steady around a minor flood peak. The river level is likely to remain above the minor flood level (4.00 m) for the next few days.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/ 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation. 
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams. 
  • Low lying riverside Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded. 
  • Parks, hiking tracks and campgrounds are likely to be closed due to flooding. To find out more go to www.parkweb.vic.gov.au/safety/flood-affected-parks. 
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Don’t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.
Road Closures:
  • Several roads are still closed in the area due to floodwater.
  • Additional roads may be damaged from heavy rain including large potholes. Please drive to the conditions.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 07/12/2023 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
